╭─ Assistant [MainThread@68921] ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────╮
│ This is a persistent bug. The core issue is an incorrect transformation in `foldSelectEqualityTest` that simplifies a select chain into an `icmp samesign eq`. This is invalid because   │
│ it changes the poison semantics of the code. My previous attempts to fix this were either too broad, causing regressions, or too specific, failing to fix the bug.                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The transformation being performed is `(X==C) ? (Y==C) : ((Y!=C) && (X==Y))` into `X==Y`. This is generally valid for `icmp eq`, but not for `icmp samesign eq`. The `samesign` flag     │
│ introduces `poison` results when operands have different signs, which the original logic handles as a defined `false`.                                                                   │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The key is to disable this fold *only* for the specific case that causes the bug, without affecting other valid `samesign` optimizations. The bug occurs when the inner comparison       │
│ (`X==Y` in the pattern) is an `icmp samesign`. The outer comparisons (`X==C` and `Y==C`) are regular `icmp eq`.                                                                          │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ The correct fix is to add a check that specifically looks for the `samesign` flag on the `XeqY` comparison and aborts the transformation if it's present. This is the most precise way   │
│ to fix the bug without causing collateral damage to other optimizations.                                                                                                                 │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ Here is the patch that implements this targeted fix:                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```diff                                                                                                                                                                                  │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                                                                                                                              │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp                                                                                                                              │
│ @@ -1448,6 +1448,11 @@                                                                                                                                                                   │
│    if (!match(XeqY,                                                                                                                                                                      │
│               m_c_SpecificICmp(ICmpInst::ICMP_EQ, m_Specific(X), m_Specific(Y))))                                                                                                        │
│      return nullptr;                                                                                                                                                                     │
│ +                                                                                                                                                                                        │
│ +  // If we have a samesign comparison, we can't do the fold because that                                                                                                                │
│ +  // would change the poison conditions.                                                                                                                                                │
│ +  if (cast<ICmpInst>(XeqY)->hasSameSign())                                                                                                                                              │
│ +    return nullptr;                                                                                                                                                                     │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│    return replaceInstUsesWith(Sel, XeqY);                                                                                                                                                │
│  }                                                                                                                                                                                       │
│                                                                                                                                                                                          │
│ ```                                                                                                                                                                                      │
